50|$|An {{intention}} to possess (sometimes called <b>animus</b> <b>possidendi)</b> {{is the other}} component of possession. All that is required is an {{intention to}} possess something for the time being. In common law countries, the intention to possess a thing is a fact. Normally, it is proved by the acts of control and surrounding circumstances.|$|E
40|$|Possession {{as a legal}} {{situation}} The thesis subject could {{be divided into two}} interconnected parts. The first part analyzes the different aspects of possession as an element of the civil law. Possession is studied as both a factual and a legal state in relations to its possible objects. Especially the subjective right as an object of possession and the impact of good faith are taken into consideration. Also two basic factors of possession - corpus possessionis and <b>animus</b> <b>possidendi</b> - are characterised. The second part focuses on possesion in concrete codes of law. Emphasis is placed on the study of possession in the new Czech Civil Code and reflections de lege ferenda. Key words: Possession Right of ownership Good faith Corpus possessionis Animus possidend...|$|E

